{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\nThe delivered epic (Gerrit stack 558/560/561/563/576/579/580/581, NOT landed) diverged\nfrom the APPROVED epic design on the authorship-payload format. bde5 (change 561,\ncommit c31fc7eb5) signs the event's RAW canonical bytes; the approved epic AC requires an\n**in-toto Statement** payload whose `subject` binds `{event_uuid, content_hash}`. This\nstory transitions the authorship *machinery* to the approved design. (User rejected the\ndelivered design; full divergence record in session_log d7c0.)\n\n## Stack scoping (why this story is authorship.py ONLY)\nThis story AMENDS Gerrit change 561 = commit c31fc7eb5 (bde5), which touches\n`src/rebar/attest/authorship.py` and NOTHING else. At that commit the authorship\nfunctions have **no consumers yet**: the write-time signing call site (`_seam.py`), the\nmerge-gate content-binding (`verify_authorship.py`), and the SNAPSHOT ledger\n(`compact.py`) are all introduced later in commit 721702e91 (3183). Therefore the\nconsumer cutover to the in-toto payload — and the epic-AC-named `create_placeholder`\nalias (which wraps `ensure_identity_for`, introduced in commit ec3aff507 / 2f13) — is\nhandled in **TS3 (117b, change 580)**, the story that reworks that commit. Keeping the\nedits in the commit where the symbols actually exist is what keeps every intermediate\npatchset internally green.\n\n## What (authorship.py machinery)\nAdd the in-toto Statement layer as NEW functions, and PRESERVE the existing low-level\nprimitive so KEY-op signing (`identity.py._verify_keyop_signature`, which signs\n`keyop_payload` bytes, not events) and any other caller keep compiling unchanged:\n\n- KEEP `sign_authorship(payload, key_path, principal)` and `verify_authorship(envelope,\n  identity_id)` as the low-level SSHSIG-over-DSSE primitive (used by KEY-op signatures).\n- `authorship_content_hash(event: dict) -> str`: **SHA-256, lowercase hex** over the\n  event's canonical JSON with the `author_sig` key EXCLUDED (the signature never covers\n  itself).\n- `build_authorship_statement(event_uuid, content_hash) -> dict`: an in-toto Statement:\n  - `_type`: `\"https://in-toto.io/Statement/v1\"`\n  - `subject`: `[{ \"name\": \"<event_uuid>\", \"digest\": { \"sha256\": \"<content_hash>\" } }]`\n  - `predicateType`: `\"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\"`\n  - `predicate`: `{}`\n- `sign_event_authorship(event: dict, key_path, principal) -> dsse.Envelope`: computes the\n  content_hash, builds the Statement, and signs its canonical JSON bytes via the primitive\n  (DSSE payloadType `application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json`, PAE-signed under the pinned\n  authorship namespace). The Statement JSON is the DSSE payload.\n- `verify_event_authorship(event: dict, envelope, identity_id, *, repo_root=None) ->\n  Verdict`: (1) parse the DSSE payload as an in-toto Statement, (2) check\n  `subject[0].name == event['uuid']` AND `subject[0].digest.sha256 ==\n  authorship_content_hash(event)`, (3) THEN verify the DSSE signature against the identity's\n  in-band keys (reusing `resolve_trust_root`). Any parse/shape failure or subject/hash\n  mismatch yields a non-verified Verdict; it NEVER raises on a lookup problem (mirrors the\n  existing fail-closed contract).\n\n## Scope\nIn: the in-toto Statement authorship machinery in `src/rebar/attest/authorship.py`\n(content_hash + Statement build + `sign_event_authorship` + `verify_event_authorship`),\nwith the low-level `sign_authorship`/`verify_authorship` primitive preserved for KEY-ops.\nOut: the write-seam stamping + merge-gate content-binding + SNAPSHOT ledger cutover to the\nnew payload AND the `create_placeholder` alias (all TS3/3183, commit 721702e91); the\nera/validity model (TS2/e165); docs/ADR (TS4/b134).\n\n## Landing / sequencing\nTS1–TS4 land as ONE ATOMIC Gerrit stack submit (relation chain), so there is no runtime\nwindow where a reworked commit is live without the others. Write-time signing is opt-in\nand the stack is unlanded, so no persisted event carries an old-format `author_sig` — no\nmigration/backfill. Docs/ADR for this pivot are rewritten in TS4.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `sign_event_authorship` produces a DSSE envelope whose payload is an in-toto\n  Statement (`_type` https://in-toto.io/Statement/v1, `predicateType`\n  application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json) with `subject[0] = {name: event_uuid,\n  digest: {sha256: content_hash}}`; a test asserts the structure + payloadType.\n- [ ] `authorship_content_hash` is SHA-256 hex over the canonical event with `author_sig`\n  EXCLUDED; a test proves adding/removing an `author_sig` key does not change the hash,\n  and mutating any other field DOES change it.\n- [ ] `verify_event_authorship` returns verified for an event signed by identity A against\n  A's in-band keys; a test asserts it does NOT verify against identity B, FAILS on a\n  tampered event body (content_hash mismatch), and FAILS on a tampered signature.\n- [ ] `verify_event_authorship` returns a non-verified Verdict (never raises) when the\n  envelope payload is not a valid in-toto Statement (malformed / missing subject) and when\n  the identity is unknown/keyless (test).\n- [ ] The low-level `sign_authorship(payload,...)` primitive is unchanged: a KEY-op-style\n  signature over `keyop_payload(...)` bytes still verifies via the primitive path (test),\n  proving the Statement layer did not break KEY-op signing.\n\n## file_impact\n- `src/rebar/attest/authorship.py` (in-toto Statement build/parse + content_hash + event sign/verify; primitive preserved)"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783882445582223001,"uuid":"80f2bb31-b266-40c4-b8e8-4ad934c02e09"}